post_text:
Dear Copper Country community members,
Thank you for the generous support for the Barkell Elementary PTO playground project can drive. With the help of our gracious volunteers who sorted through over 23,000 cans and bottles and generous cash donations, we were able to raise $3,527.99 toward the playground project.
Our sponsors and volunteers included:
Thrivent, through an Alpha Delta Kappa sister, sponsored our start up.
Alpha Delta Kappa, a teacher sorority, gave input, and sorority sisters volunteered to organize, sort, and donate.
Barkell Elementary teachers and support staff volunteered to sort.
Hancock Public Schools administration for advice and guidance and publicity and volunteered to sort.
Barkell Elementary PTO for organizing the signup and for having the project in place.
Parents who volunteered to sort.
Teacher spouse who transported the bags of cans and bottles to Pepsi in Houghton in his truck and trailer.

Ever in your gratitude,
Gladys Dupuis and Christy HIlgers
Alpha Delta Kappa
Gamma Alpha chapter

post_text:
Happy "Last Day of School" to all of our Bulldog families! We all cannot thank you enough for all the effort you all put in through this crazy time, and all through the year. It was a fun school year, with lots of pride and energy and that's what makes our school so special -- so THANK YOU! Teachers and staff all truly hope you get to enjoy this summer break entirely with whatever plans you have in store. We have missed you since March, and we'll miss you through the summer!

*Please note, today is "packet drop off day" where any remaining work should be dropped off to the school.*

Hancock Athletic Booster Club
June 3 at 5:48 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to D‚ÄôAndra Kero who received the Senior Female Athlete of the Year Award!üíõ‚ù§Ô∏è

D‚ÄôAndra competed in the sports of volleyball, basketball, and softball during her tenure at HCH, earning 3 varsity letters in volleyball, 4 in basketball, and 3 in softball.
She was team captain of the volleyball team, earning second team all conference accolades, and was named team offensive player of the year for the 2019 season. D'Andra was a four year starter for the basketball team, earning all conference honors, all conference second team, and all conference first team awards the past 3 seasons respectively, while serving as a team captain during her senior campaign and being recognized as an All-U.P. Honorable Mention for the 2019-2020 season. She also started for the softball team for three seasons, earning all conference honors her sophomore and junior seasons, and was a part of the district championship team in 2019.
D'Andra is a 4 year honor roll student, with a cumulative 3.74 GPA.
She will be attending MTU in the Fall.

shared_text:
Hancock Athletic Booster Club
June 3 at 5:49 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to Colton Salani who received the Senior Male Athlete of the Year Award!
üíõ‚ù§Ô∏è

Colton Salani competed in the sports of football, hockey, track, golf and baseball during his tenure at HCH, earning a cumulative 14 varsity letters. In football, Colton earned All-Conference Honorable Mention (x2), First Team All-Conference, First Team All-UP and Second Team All-State accolades as the starting QB for the Bulldogs during his four years. He also served as captain of both the football and hockey teams his senior year. In track, Colton qualified and competed in the UP State finals in each his freshman through junior years.
Colton is a 4 year honor roll student, with a cumulative 3.82 GPA and a member of the National Honor Society.
He will be attending MTU in the Fall where he will compete as a member of the MTU Huskies Football program.

post_text: Good morning! Today is the day our seniors have been waiting for! No matter the circumstances, let's make this the best day for our graduates. Come out and celebrate these fine individuals at our parade, beginning at 10am with live coverage online and a broadcast from Mix 93.5. The commencement again is exclusive to only immediate family, but will continue to stream for family and friends near and far through the ceremony. Remember through this occasion, continue to safely social distance and practice hand washing and sanitizing through the day. The Hancock Schools can't wait to celebrate this day with everybody, and we are so very proud of this group. Today is YOUR day Bulldogs. Go out and do great things in this world! üêæ‚ù§üíõüåé

post_text: I am very proud to present the "Hancock High School Senior Showcase video." When this unfortunate event occuring, we wanted to come up ways to highlight these amazing students. This was a voluntary event -- and about 20 of our seniors took part in relishing in their Bulldog stories, advice to underclassmen and what their future holds. It is a lengthy film with about 30 minutes of story telling, but it is a video to cherish so please take some time to watch and listen to these great kids. We are so very proud of everybody, and I think this was a very wonderful way to pay tribute to what these students will really miss as high school students. <3 Please enjoy!

Students who have worked on and turned in materials/assignments from 3 or more subject areas have been recognized weekly! Our Outstanding students who went above and beyond in and demonstrated great work ethic were provided a $10 dollar gift card to Culvers! Thank you to the parents who help ensure the students are working to their full potential! We know it's not an easy time for anyone, so keep doing your best in all that you're doing! Go Bulldogs! *One more important piece to note is that this work was prior to the new requirements implemented as of Friday.*

Hancock Athletic Booster Club
September 2, 2019 at 7:40 PM ¬∑

Happy First Day of School tomorrow to all our Bulldogs!! üíõ‚ù§Ô∏è

A message from Mr. Salani-
The High School first hour of the day will be dedicated to a Welcome Back 'experience' where we will share in a full assembly in the High School gymnasium; a continental style breakfast for the students will be available in our commons and cafeteria; our Cheer Team will be having an 'Iced Coffee Fundraiser' for $2.00 a cup, as well as face painting; students can become more familiar with their lockers, locks and location; and students will also have the opportunity to visit with faculty, both new and returning.

We will then begin the first period at 9:10 AM and conduct 45 minute abbreviated class periods for the day.
